<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={5.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={6.12}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={6.83}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={5.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={6.12}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={6.83}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>45.01</li><li>59.96</li><li>76.62</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{5}^{{2}}={6.12}^{{2}}+{6.83}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({6.12}\right)}{\left({6.83}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{25}={37.4544}+{46.6489}-{83.5992}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{59.1033}=-{83.5992}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.70698403812477}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={45.00994481928}={45.01}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({45.00994481928}\right)}}}}{{5.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{6.12}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1.0478487671475}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left({1.0478487671475}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={59.956885267169}\approx{59.96}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{45.00994481928}+{59.956885267169}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={76.619731571638}\approx{76.62}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

